# ADR-0019 — AI Operating System Architecture

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

Traditional software systems are typically organized around applications.

Examples include:

- CRM systems
- ERPs
- Websites
- Mobile applications

AI systems are often organized around:

- chat interfaces
- prompts
- LLM providers

Neither model adequately represents the long-term vision of Pharos.

Pharos is intended to become an AI Operating System capable of supporting
multiple companies, products, users, Agents and execution environments.

The architecture therefore requires a clear definition of its fundamental
layers.

---

# Decision

The platform is organized into independent architectural layers.

Each layer owns a distinct responsibility.

```
+------------------------------------------------------+
|                User Interfaces                       |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| Chat | Voice | API | CLI | Mobile | Web | Scheduler  |
+------------------------------------------------------+
                        │
                        ▼
+------------------------------------------------------+
|                    AI Agents                         |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| CEO | Engineering | Marketing | Sales | Finance ...  |
+------------------------------------------------------+
                        │
                        ▼
+------------------------------------------------------+
|                Intelligence Layer                    |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| Memory | Knowledge | Company Brain | Reasoning       |
+------------------------------------------------------+
                        │
                        ▼
+------------------------------------------------------+
|                    Runtime                           |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| Intent | Planning | Workflow | Execution | Streaming |
+------------------------------------------------------+
                        │
                        ▼
+------------------------------------------------------+
|                 Capability Layer                     |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| Tools | Plugins | Integrations | External Services   |
+------------------------------------------------------+
                        │
                        ▼
+------------------------------------------------------+
|              External Infrastructure                 |
|------------------------------------------------------|
| Files | Git | Databases | APIs | Cloud | Devices     |
+------------------------------------------------------+
```

Every layer communicates only through published contracts.

---

# Layer Responsibilities

## User Interface Layer

Responsible for interaction.

Examples:

- Chat
- Mobile
- Web
- Voice
- API

Never performs reasoning.

---

## Agent Layer

Responsible for intelligence.

Agents:

- reason
- plan
- retrieve knowledge
- retrieve memory
- create RuntimeIntent

Agents never execute work directly.

---

## Intelligence Layer

Provides information required for reasoning.

Includes:

- Memory
- Knowledge
- Company Brain

Does not perform execution.

---

## Runtime Layer

Responsible only for execution.

Includes:

- RuntimeIntent
- RuntimePlanner
- RuntimeEngine
- WorkflowBuilder
- Workflow

Runtime never performs reasoning.

---

## Capability Layer

Provides executable capabilities.

Examples:

- Tools
- Plugins
- External integrations

Capabilities extend the platform without modifying Runtime.

---

## Infrastructure Layer

Contains implementation-specific systems.

Examples:

- databases
- cloud providers
- Git repositories
- local files
- external APIs

Infrastructure is replaceable.

---

# Architectural Principles

## Layer Independence

Each layer has exactly one responsibility.

---

## Dependency Direction

Dependencies always point downward.

Higher layers may depend on lower-layer contracts.

Lower layers never depend on higher layers.

---

## Replaceability

Every layer may be replaced independently.

Examples:

Replace Runtime.

Agents remain unchanged.

Replace Knowledge Provider.

Runtime remains unchanged.

Replace LLM.

Architecture remains unchanged.

---

## AI Independence

The architecture does not depend on any specific AI model.

Examples:

- OpenAI
- Anthropic
- Gemini
- Local models

All are implementation details.

---

## Company Independence

The Runtime is reusable across organizations.

Company Brain is organization-specific.

---

# Dependency Rules

User Interfaces never execute Tools directly.

Agents never access infrastructure directly.

Runtime never retrieves knowledge.

Capabilities never perform reasoning.

Infrastructure never depends on Runtime.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Monolithic AI Application

Rejected.

Poor separation of concerns.

---

## LLM-Centric Architecture

Rejected.

LLMs are replaceable providers,
not architectural foundations.

---

## Runtime-Centric Everything

Rejected.

Runtime should execute,
not own intelligence.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- clear boundaries
- scalable architecture
- independent evolution
- provider independence
- reusable Runtime
- reusable Agents
- easier testing
- long-term maintainability

Negative:

- additional architectural complexity
- more contracts
- more documentation

These costs are justified for an AI Operating System.

---

# Future Evolution

Future architectural layers may include:

- Security
- Governance
- Observability
- Distributed Runtime
- Marketplace
- Enterprise Administration

These extensions should integrate without changing existing layers.

